Loudoun County ([/ˈlaʊdən/](/Help:IPA/English)) is, as I said, in the northern part of [Virginia](/Virginia). It’s part of that sprawling [Washington–Arlington–Alexandria, DC–VA–MD–WV Metropolitan Statistical Area](/Washington_metropolitan_area). A cog in a larger machine, really.

And the income. As of 2023, the median household income was $156,821. &#91;5&#93; The highest in the nation, they say. &#91;6&#93; Funny, isn’t it? All that money, and the motto is still "I Byde My Time." What are they waiting for?

### History

#### 18th century

*The early days.* When the land was still being wrestled into submission.

William and Sarah Nettle House in [Waterford](/Waterford,_Virginia)

Loudoun County was carved out of [Fairfax County](/Fairfax_County,_Virginia) in 1757. Named for some Earl, [John Campbell](/John_Campbell,_4th_Earl_of_Loudoun), who was also the governor general. &#91;1&#93; The real settlement, though, started earlier, in the 1720s and 30s. [Quakers](/Religious_Society_of_Friends), [Scots-Irish](/Scotch-Irish_American), [Germans](/German_American), and others filtering down from [Pennsylvania](/Province_of_Pennsylvania) and [Maryland](/Province_of_Maryland). And then there were the ones moving upriver from [Tidewater](/Tidewater_region_of_Virginia) – the [English](/English_people) and the [enslaved Africans](/History_of_slavery). A real melting pot, if you like your metaphors lukewarm. &#91;7&#93;

By the time the [American Revolution](/American_Revolution) kicked off, Loudoun was the most populous county in Virginia. And it was feeding the war effort. Wheat, mostly. Enough to earn it the rather dramatic nickname, "[Breadbasket](/Breadbasket) of the Revolution." &#91;8&#93; A lot of good that did them in the long run.

#### 19th century

*The century of conflict and… presidential residences.*

During the [War of 1812](/War_of_1812), they apparently packed up all the important government documents and hid them here, in [Leesburg](/Leesburg,_Virginia). &#91;9&#93; Said to be at [Rokeby House](/Rokeby_(Leesburg,_Virginia)). &#91;10&#93; Hiding secrets. Seems to be a recurring theme.

Then there was [James Monroe](/James_Monroe). The president. He treated [Oak Hill Plantation](/Oak_Hill_(James_Monroe_house)) like home from 1823 until he died there. &#91;11&#93; They even say the county’s coat of arms and flag are a nod to his [Monroe Doctrine](/Monroe_Doctrine) and some supposed special relationship with [Britain](/Great_Britain). &#91;12&#93; All very official.

The [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War). Of course. It split the county, as it did everything else. Its strategic location meant fighting. For more on that dreary business, see [Loudoun County in the American Civil War](/Loudoun_County_in_the_American_Civil_War). Both of Loudoun’s representatives at the [Virginia Secession Convention](/Virginia_Secession_Convention) were against leaving the Union. But the voters… they went along. Units formed here, and others went north to join the federals. The [Battle of Ball's Bluff](/Battle_of_Ball%27s_Bluff) happened near [Leesburg](/Leesburg,_Virginia). Even [Oliver Wendell Holmes Jr.](/Oliver_Wendell_Holmes_Jr.), the future Supreme Court justice, got shot there. The Union troops occupied Leesburg, then the Confederates took it back. And then there was [John S. Mosby](/John_S._Mosby), the partisan. He based his operations around here and [Fauquier County](/Fauquier_County,_Virginia). &#91;13&#93; During the [Gettysburg campaign](/Gettysburg_campaign), [J.E.B. Stuart](/J.E.B._Stuart) and the Union cavalry had a go at each other in the battles of [Aldie](/Battle_of_Aldie), [Middleburg](/Battle_of_Middleburg), and [Upperville](/Battle_of_Upperville). By the end of 1863, the Union had control. And the county sent delegates to this reconstructed Virginia General Assembly. &#91;14&#93; Downey, Mercer, Henshaw, Bentley, Gray. &#91;15&#93; Names in the dust.

#### 20th century

*The century of innovation, war, and… airports.*

[World War I](/World_War_I) saw Loudoun farmers stepping up. New techniques, better yields. They were churning out wheat like mad – over a million bushels in 1917. &#91;16&#93; Much of it went to training camps. After the war, a plaque went up. For the "30 glorious dead." Twenty-five of them died not even fighting, just in training or back home. Glorious.

Then, in 1962, they built [Dulles International Airport](/Dulles_International_Airport) in the southeast. And things… changed. A high-tech boom, rapid growth. People flocked to the eastern part, creating these planned communities: Sterling Park, [Sugarland Run](/Sugarland_Run,_Virginia), Cascades, [Ashburn Village](/Ashburn_Village), Ashburn Farm. It became part of the Washington suburbs. Meanwhile, the western part, the Loudoun Valley, stayed more rural, dotted with small towns. &#91;8&#93; A tale of two Loudouns.

